{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567820","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567820"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:08:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:08:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19451"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19451","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19451"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.11,0.79,0.02,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12178"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84850"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12178","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12178"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19451"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69139"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"393"},{"type":"tags","id":"1138"},{"type":"tags","id":"3564"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"28807"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28809"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28870"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84850","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/84850"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic concerned about a mole on her right ear that her partner noticed has changed over the past three months (Image). She has fair skin and red hair, with a history of frequent sunburns in her youth. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is an asymmetrical pigmented lesion on her right pinna measuring 8 mm in diameter. The lesion has irregular borders and contains areas of brown, black, and blue-black coloration. The patient confirms the lesion was previously smaller and uniform in colour.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Squamous cell carcinoma","Basal cell carcinoma","Malignant melanoma","Solar keratosis","Seborrhoeic keratosis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a pigmented lesion demonstrating multiple features concerning for melanoma. The ABCDE criteria for melanoma are all present: Asymmetry, Border irregularity, Colour variation (brown, black, and blue-black), Diameter \u0026gt;6 mm (8 mm), and Evolution (recent change). The patient\u0027s fair skin type and history of sunburns are additional risk factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMalignant melanoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as a changing pigmented lesion. The presence of multiple colours, especially blue-black areas, is particularly concerning for melanoma as it suggests different depths of pigment within the lesion. Melanomas of the ear are particularly concerning as they have a higher risk of metastasis due to the rich lymphatic drainage of this area.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESquamous cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as a firm, tender, non-healing ulcer or nodule. It is usually non-pigmented and may have a keratotic surface. While it can be aggressive, it does not typically show the colour variation seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBasal cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E classically appears as a pearly nodule with telangiectasia, often with central ulceration. While pigmented variants exist, they do not typically show the rapid change or multiple colours described here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESolar keratosis\u003C/strong\u003E presents as a rough, scaly patch on sun-damaged skin. These lesions are typically flat, red or skin-coloured, and do not show the pigmentation pattern described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeborrhoeic keratosis\u003C/strong\u003E appears as a \u0027stuck-on\u0027 warty growth with a waxy, scaly surface. While these can be pigmented, they typically have a more uniform colour and do not show the concerning changes in size and colour described here.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The ABCDE criteria (Asymmetry, Border irregularity, Colour variation, Diameter \u003E6mm, Evolution) are key features suggesting melanoma","Recent change in size, shape or colour of a pigmented lesion is a concerning feature for melanoma","Any pigmented lesion with multiple colours, especially black or blue-black areas, should raise suspicion for melanoma"],"references":["Clarke P. Benign pigmented skin lesions. Aust J Gen Pract. 2019;48(6):364-367. doi:10.31128/AJGP-12-18-4802","Rourke L, Oberholtzer S, Chatterley T, Brassard A. Learning to detect, categorize, and identify skin lesions: a meta-analysis. JAMA Dermatol. 2015;151(3):293-301. doi:10.1001/jamadermatol.2014.3300"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69139"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19451"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21535"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21535","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21535"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/PSOiujg2V6ZpXlBjwORv5fMBiouE1d.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/PSOiujg2V6ZpXlBjwORv5fMBiouE1d.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":361,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69139","lin